<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: FULLERTON; CITY SEEKS GROUPS TO ADOPT LOCAL PARKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIMI KO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The city is seeking nonprofit community organizations to adopt a local park 
for 15 weeks and get paid $325. 
</P>
<P>
 The groups chosen to adopt parks are expected to visit their parks at least 
once a week between Sept. 26 and Jan. 22 and keep them clean. 
</P>
<P>
 Cleaning duties include picking up paper, cans, glass and other litter, city 
officials said. Other responsibilities include reporting to authorities any 
dangerous objects, broken equipment or suspicious activities. 
</P>
<P>
 Organizations interested in applying to adopt a park must have more than 50 
members and provide a list of local activities they have or plan to participate 
in or sponsor. Deadline to apply for the program is 5 p.m. Sept. 9. 
Applications are available at City Hall. Eligible applicants will be selected 
at random. 
</P>
<P>
 The parks and playgrounds up for adoption are: Acacia, Adlena, Amerige, 
Beechwood, Brea Dam, Byerrum, Chapman, Fern, Ford, Gilman, Grissom, 
Independence, Hermosa, Hillcrest, Ladera Vista, Laguna Lake, Laguna Road, 
Lemon, Nature, Nicolas, Orangethorpe, Pacific Drive, Richman, Rolling Hills, 
Valencia and Woodcrest. MIMI KO 
</P>
</TEXT>
